00:27:25.667 --> 00:27:27.209
Good morning, Mom.

245
00:27:28.126 --> 00:27:29.584
Good morning, Tomek.

246
00:27:29.959 --> 00:27:31.417
May I come in?

247
00:27:33.584 --> 00:27:35.626
This is your house too.

248
00:27:38.792 --> 00:27:42.251
- Hi, Pops.
- Hi, Tomek.


249
00:27:44.417 --> 00:27:46.792
Mommy, come here for a sec...

250
00:27:48.709 --> 00:27:51.709
I have a problem.

251
00:27:53.042 --> 00:27:59.251
Helena locked herself in the bathroom
again. She doesn't want to come out.


252
00:27:59.417 --> 00:28:05.292
Dunno if she's drowning herself
in there or what. I'm dead scared.


253
00:28:06.001 --> 00:28:07.792
Go to your father. Go on.

254
00:28:07.959 --> 00:28:11.084
- I don't want to be with her anymore.
- Sure, sure.


255
00:28:12.417 --> 00:28:14.417
Thanks, Mommy.

256
00:28:16.126 --> 00:28:18.501
Jeez. I feel like an idiot.

257
00:28:22.834 --> 00:28:25.876
I have a tape
I wanted you to copy.

258
00:28:28.709 --> 00:28:32.292
And on top of that
I have those damn classes this week...


259
00:28:33.917 --> 00:28:36.542
As far as I'm concerned,
you don't have to graduate.


260
00:28:36.709 --> 00:28:38.834
There's no point if you don't want to.

261
00:28:39.001 --> 00:28:42.626
You could keep learning on your own.
You're great at it.


262
00:28:44.751 --> 00:28:46.876
Make a living teaching English.

263
00:28:51.167 --> 00:28:55.126
Any idiot could graduate,
so that's what I'm going to do.


264
00:28:56.084 --> 00:28:58.292
I ordered those tapes for you already.

265
00:28:58.459 --> 00:29:00.751
I'll bring them over
as soon as they get here.


266
00:29:02.167 --> 00:29:06.751
I'll spend the night.

267
00:29:07.417 --> 00:29:09.292
Oh, joy!

268
00:29:11.334 --> 00:29:14.792
Where is that... Ah, OK.

269
00:29:42.209 --> 00:29:43.876
How about...

270
00:29:48.126 --> 00:29:54.084
If the entirety of our family life
and interaction


271
00:29:54.292 --> 00:30:00.334
is going to consist of kicking
right in the most vulnerable spots,


272
00:30:00.542 --> 00:30:07.626
if that's going to be
the extent of our intimacy...


273
00:30:07.792 --> 00:30:10.376
I get it, Zosia.

274
00:30:10.542 --> 00:30:14.501
But no one promised that family life
would be sunshine and rainbows.


275
00:30:14.667 --> 00:30:17.167
All right, the Church does promise that,

276
00:30:17.334 --> 00:30:21.126
and the Constitution states
that the family is the basic unit


277
00:30:21.292 --> 00:30:23.834
of the Socialist society and so on...

278
00:30:24.001 --> 00:30:28.334
But nowhere is it implicitly said that
a family is anything but a group of people


279
00:30:28.501 --> 00:30:31.376
who like and dislike each other
in equal measure.


280
00:30:31.542 --> 00:30:36.959
According to Jungian theory,
every major one-sided emotion


281
00:30:37.167 --> 00:30:40.042
goes along with its powerful,

282
00:30:40.209 --> 00:30:45.709
suppressed opposite,
which will eventually raise its head.


283
00:30:45.959 --> 00:30:48.834
If you loved
your mother or father as a child,


284
00:30:49.001 --> 00:30:52.459
after a while you're
going to feel like beating them up...


285
00:30:53.917 --> 00:30:56.376
I don't know if that's right.

286
00:30:57.292 --> 00:31:00.959
I've never felt this way.

287
00:31:01.709 --> 00:31:04.542
I think I have.

288
00:31:13.959 --> 00:31:18.459
Today's guest of our radio station's
first Top Hits program


289
00:31:18.626 --> 00:31:22.501
is the young Tomasz Beksinski.

290
00:31:23.167 --> 00:31:26.167
Before the broadcast Tomek
asked me to call him the Enthusiast -


291
00:31:26.334 --> 00:31:28.667
an enthusiast of good music.

292
00:31:28.834 --> 00:31:34.334
He's going to play us a new record
from his massive collection.


293
00:31:34.501 --> 00:31:38.001
For the first time on Polish radio

294
00:31:38.167 --> 00:31:40.917
a guest will have the mic.

295
00:31:41.084 --> 00:31:42.792
Good morning.

296
00:31:43.709 --> 00:31:45.376
I'm Tomek.

297
00:31:45.542 --> 00:31:48.084
Tomasz Beksinski.

298
00:31:48.251 --> 00:31:52.667
I'd like to play the debut album
of the British duo Yazoo:


299
00:31:52.834 --> 00:31:55.626
"Upstairs at Eric's."

300
00:31:55.792 --> 00:32:02.084
This is a brand-new record, of course,
it came out some 3 months ago.


301
00:32:03.292 --> 00:32:07.959
This British band
was formed by Vincent Clarke,


302
00:32:08.126 --> 00:32:11.626
formerly of Depeche Mode,
along with Alison Moyet.


303
00:32:11.792 --> 00:32:17.959
Let's start with the
first track: "Don't Go".


304
00:32:28.584 --> 00:32:31.167
- Attaboy!
- Yes!


305
00:32:32.751 --> 00:32:37.292
I'll be afraid to switch on the radio.
It's a little amateurish.


306
00:32:38.084 --> 00:32:41.667
I've been thinking about that man who's
coming tomorrow. He could be important.


307
00:32:41.834 --> 00:32:45.251
- I'll turn it up for you, Ma.
- Thank you.


308
00:33:12.626 --> 00:33:15.709
- I think it's him.
- With a dame?


309
00:33:18.417 --> 00:33:20.501
No, alone.

310
00:33:25.792 --> 00:33:29.584
- Just stay calm, Zosia.
- I'm calm.


311
00:33:32.959 --> 00:33:35.167
- Please come in!
- Good morning.


312
00:33:35.334 --> 00:33:37.334
Come on in.

313
00:33:37.501 --> 00:33:40.001
My name is Piotr Dmochowski.

314
00:33:40.167 --> 00:33:43.126
I'm an attorney with
a law firm in Paris.

315
00:33:43.292 --> 00:33:46.501
- In Paris!
- Zdzislaw Beksinski, engineer, M.Sc.


316
00:33:46.667 --> 00:33:50.584
This is my mother, Stanislawa Beksinska.
Retired Polish teacher.


317
00:33:52.792 --> 00:33:56.834
This is my wife, Zofia Beksinska.
She has a degree in Romance studies.


318
00:33:57.001 --> 00:34:00.417
- Pleased to meet you.
<i>- Guten morgen!</i>


319
00:34:00.584 --> 00:34:04.917
- And this... is my firstborn.
- Tomasz! Beksinski as well.


320
00:34:05.084 --> 00:34:08.626
- Movie translator, radio show host...
- An Enthusiast!


321
00:34:08.917 --> 00:34:12.834
- A genius father and a genius son...
- And the Holy Spirit.


322
00:34:13.001 --> 00:34:15.209
Amen!

323
00:34:15.376 --> 00:34:17.709
Come into the living room.

324
00:34:18.751 --> 00:34:22.167
- Can I get you something to drink?
- No, thank you.


325
00:34:22.334 --> 00:34:25.626
- I don't want to be a bother.
- That's no bother at all...


326
00:34:28.834 --> 00:34:33.459
I've been a longtime
admirer of your talent.


327
00:34:33.626 --> 00:34:35.001
I don't want to be a bother,

328
00:34:35.167 --> 00:34:42.959
but if you could allow me
to see your latest paintings


329
00:34:43.376 --> 00:34:45.417
and purchase a few
for my private collection.


330
00:34:45.584 --> 00:34:49.042
I'm not in charge of selling my paintings.

331
00:34:49.209 --> 00:34:54.834
The art gallery I work with
has exclusive sales rights in Poland.


332
00:34:55.292 --> 00:34:57.167
How about abroad?

333
00:34:57.876 --> 00:35:03.834
If they're to be taken abroad, you're
welcome to interact with them directly.


334
00:35:04.209 --> 00:35:07.834
- I'm glad to hear this.
- Likewise!


335
00:35:10.334 --> 00:35:14.209
Oh, by the way...
Stanislawa Stankiewicz,


336
00:35:14.376 --> 00:35:16.584
Zosia's mother, a farmer,
lives in our flat as well,


337
00:35:16.751 --> 00:35:19.292
but she's asleep at the moment.

338
00:35:19.459 --> 00:35:21.959
This isn't what I expected.
You seem so upbeat...


339
00:35:22.126 --> 00:35:23.292
Me, upbeat?!

340
00:35:23.459 --> 00:35:26.292
Your home and family
look so ordinary, too.


341
00:35:26.459 --> 00:35:29.501
I was expecting a gloomy castle...

342
00:35:29.667 --> 00:35:34.292
We chased our rats
and spiders out for a walk,


343
00:35:34.459 --> 00:35:37.751
stuffed all our skeletons
in closets, don't you know...


344
00:35:37.917 --> 00:35:40.876
Oh, I'm sure.
You have a delightful sense of humor.


345
00:35:41.042 --> 00:35:43.542
Is this your studio?

346
00:35:44.042 --> 00:35:46.792
- The Holy Land, of course...
- It's never been holy.


347
00:35:46.959 --> 00:35:48.709
Christ!

348
00:35:49.251 --> 00:35:51.042
That's from the 70s.

349
00:35:51.209 --> 00:35:53.417
The fantastic period?

350
00:35:53.584 --> 00:35:57.417
I didn't choose this label
and I don't particularly like it.


351
00:35:57.584 --> 00:35:59.542
Are they for sale?

352
00:35:59.709 --> 00:36:01.584
They belong to my wife.

353
00:36:01.751 --> 00:36:03.459
They're my retirement fund.

354
00:36:03.626 --> 00:36:05.667
A marvellous collection!
Congratulations!


355
00:36:05.834 --> 00:36:09.667
- Thank you.
- I'd snap them right up if I could.


356
00:36:10.126 --> 00:36:16.626
Sorry, I couldn't do without them.
They're my pets.


357
00:36:17.667 --> 00:36:20.917
I have 9 in total...
Come, I'll show you the rest.


358
00:36:21.084 --> 00:36:24.126
Oh, I'm sorry. Go on in.

359
00:36:24.292 --> 00:36:27.167
Wonderful!

360
00:36:28.251 --> 00:36:30.167
Marvellous!

361
00:36:51.334 --> 00:36:52.917
I didn't know you were a ghost.

362
00:36:53.084 --> 00:36:55.417
- That's just one of these things.
- Performance art?


363
00:36:55.584 --> 00:37:01.709
More like a joke, a farewell to Sanok...
But no one thought it was funny.


364
00:37:02.334 --> 00:37:03.959
Incredible!

365
00:37:05.459 --> 00:37:12.042
My father painted these between

366
00:37:12.792 --> 00:37:18.001
He improved significantly back in '74.
That's these two...


367
00:37:23.542 --> 00:37:27.167
I think I like
this head most of all.

368
00:37:30.084 --> 00:37:34.667
I liked about 75%
of that year's paintings.


369
00:37:35.251 --> 00:37:41.417
75% were cool, 50% were decent,

370
00:37:41.709 --> 00:37:45.876
awesome, and 5% of these
were absolutely amazing.


371
00:37:46.042 --> 00:37:48.376
If you compared
that crap to his present...


372
00:37:48.542 --> 00:37:52.459
- So your father's evolving artistically?
- Could be.


373
00:37:52.626 --> 00:37:55.917
There's something about his art

374
00:37:56.084 --> 00:37:58.501
that he doesn't deign
to notice about beat bands.


375
00:37:58.667 --> 00:38:01.959
He thinks every new album
is worse than the last.


376
00:38:02.126 --> 00:38:05.168
He doesn't let Mom and me
talk about his paintings,


377
00:38:05.334 --> 00:38:07.334
says it gives him painter's block.

378
00:38:07.501 --> 00:38:12.459
This one's from this year,
the last one I managed to beg off of him.


379
00:38:12.626 --> 00:38:17.209
There are 13 paintings in my collection.
Guess that's gonna be it.


380
00:38:17.376 --> 00:38:19.126
They're masterpieces.

381
00:38:19.292 --> 00:38:21.917
Even better
than your mother's collection.


382
00:38:22.459 --> 00:38:27.042
Could you entertain the idea
of ever selling them to me?


383
00:38:32.042 --> 00:38:34.126
- What if I...
- No!


384
00:38:36.001 --> 00:38:37.959
All right, I won't insist.

385
00:38:38.959 --> 00:38:40.501
Fantastic.

386
00:38:42.667 --> 00:38:45.084
Would you let me
look at them a little longer?


387
00:38:45.251 --> 00:38:47.417
All right.

388
00:38:52.084 --> 00:38:54.751
He reminds me of Ferdinand the Bull.

389
00:38:54.917 --> 00:38:57.042
- I don't know...
- Sure, Zosia,


390
00:38:57.209 --> 00:39:01.334
but I have the impression that he's here
on behalf of some rich French businessman


391
00:39:01.501 --> 00:39:03.376
who'd rather remain anonymous.

392
00:39:03.542 --> 00:39:07.042
After going on and on about
the importance of creative freedom


393
00:39:07.209 --> 00:39:11.417
you're going to hitch yourself
to the wheel now?!


394
00:39:11.584 --> 00:39:15.251
He's not forcing me into anything!
I have to provide 12 paintings per year,


395
00:39:15.417 --> 00:39:18.001
out of my 20-odd yearly average.

396
00:39:18.167 --> 00:39:23.042
$12,000 a year is a fortune in Poland!

397
00:39:23.667 --> 00:39:26.126
I'll be able to focus on painting

398
00:39:26.292 --> 00:39:29.959
without worrying about money,
about our grandmothers, or about you!


399
00:39:30.126 --> 00:39:34.001
- 12,000 dollars?!
- Oops! Excuse me...


400
00:39:37.626 --> 00:39:42.167
Zosia... Let me make
one thing clear right away:


401
00:39:42.376 --> 00:39:44.209
no need to pass around
the Christmas wafer!


402
00:39:44.376 --> 00:39:47.501
No hugging or, 
God forbid, kissing.

403
00:39:47.667 --> 00:39:52.626
I don't do it myself and I don't ask
that of anyone. All the best, folks!


404
00:39:53.001 --> 00:39:54.459
Tuck in.

405
00:39:56.251 --> 00:39:58.626
- Beksinski...
- I like beer!


406
00:39:58.834 --> 00:40:02.126
I know exactly what you mean.
I'm not big on beer...


407
00:40:02.292 --> 00:40:06.084
- And cigarettes even less so.
- There'll be time to talk later.


408
00:40:06.251 --> 00:40:08.709
- Turn off the TV.
- Okay, I'll just find Channel 3.


409
00:40:08.876 --> 00:40:10.584
Turn it off!

410
00:40:11.792 --> 00:40:13.876
This makes me wet.

411
00:40:14.792 --> 00:40:18.126
In the name of the Father
and Son and the Holy Spirit. Amen.


412
00:40:18.292 --> 00:40:22.459
Our Father, who art in heaven,
hallowed be Thy name,


413
00:40:22.626 --> 00:40:25.751
- Thy kingdom come...
- What'd you buy?


414
00:40:25.917 --> 00:40:28.209
- Guess.
- Where's my present?


415
00:40:28.959 --> 00:40:31.709
Check down there.

416
00:40:32.209 --> 00:40:35.042
See, son?

417
00:40:35.292 --> 00:40:38.084
- Gotcha!
- Exactly.


418
00:40:40.542 --> 00:40:43.376
Gotcha, buddy!

419
00:40:44.584 --> 00:40:46.584
- Give it here!
- Got scissors?


420
00:41:49.959 --> 00:41:52.917
<i>This is Zdzislaw Beksinski.</i>

421
00:41:55.626 --> 00:41:58.334
<i>Today is...</i>

422
00:42:03.876 --> 00:42:07.834
<i>And this is my beloved spouse!</i>

423
00:42:09.126 --> 00:42:14.376
<i>Your beloved spouse
is feeling extremely camera-shy.</i>


424
00:42:14.834 --> 00:42:16.709
<i>But why, Zosia?</i>

425
00:42:17.959 --> 00:42:20.334
<i>Don't bother me
or I'll spoil the pierogi!</i>


426
00:42:20.501 --> 00:42:23.542
<i>You'll see yourself...</i>

427
00:42:23.917 --> 00:42:25.584
<i>Get on with it.</i>

428
00:42:26.917 --> 00:42:28.917
<i>I don't have time for that!</i>

429
00:42:29.084 --> 00:42:31.167
<i>Zoom in on my face.</i>

430
00:42:32.126 --> 00:42:36.042
<i>Jeez! It's zooming on its own! How come?</i>

431
00:42:36.209 --> 00:42:40.001
<i>You can set it to automatic zoom.</i>

432
00:42:40.167 --> 00:42:43.542
<i>- What an awful closeup.
- Is it an awful closeup?</i>


433
00:42:44.334 --> 00:42:46.792
<i>Yes. Here you go.</i>

434
00:42:48.792 --> 00:42:51.834
<i>I filmed the whole room already, Tomek.</i>

435
00:42:52.126 --> 00:42:58.334
<i>But I'm feeling a bit neglected
and under-recorded myself.</i>


436
00:42:59.501 --> 00:43:01.626
<i>- I'm going to bed, Zdzisiu.
- I'm coming!</i>


437
00:43:01.792 --> 00:43:03.751
<i>Let him get me on film.</i>

438
00:43:04.251 --> 00:43:05.959
<i>Wait a moment, will you?</i>

439
00:43:07.667 --> 00:43:12.501
<i>Zdzislaw Beksinski. 
Incredible!</i>

440
00:43:13.417 --> 00:43:16.501
Introducing Ultravox
and their biggest hit-


441
00:43:16.667 --> 00:43:18.251
"Dancing with Tears in my Eyes".

442
00:43:18.417 --> 00:43:23.459
Weeping for the memory
of a life gone by...

443
00:43:23.626 --> 00:43:26.376
This is exactly what I wanted to do
today in Rzeszow!


444
00:44:09.751 --> 00:44:12.292
- What's your name?
- Patrycja.


445
00:44:18.292 --> 00:44:20.334
<i>Patrycja: Forever and ever.</i>

446
00:44:41.334 --> 00:44:43.001
What a fabulous room!

447
00:44:45.959 --> 00:44:49.417
- Are these all yours?
- Yes, of course!


448
00:44:50.084 --> 00:44:54.876
- Could you put them back in their spots?
- Are these your pictures?


449
00:44:55.042 --> 00:44:57.709
My old man painted them, so they're mine,

450
00:44:57.876 --> 00:45:02.542
as in, they belong to me.
Because this is my crypt.


451
00:45:03.167 --> 00:45:05.459
Mind if I smoke?

452
00:45:05.709 --> 00:45:07.751
Well... Sure, but...

453
00:45:11.251 --> 00:45:16.751
This is my collection of LPs
and reel-to-reel tapes.


454
00:45:19.209 --> 00:45:21.167
Mind if I kiss you?

455
00:45:22.084 --> 00:45:25.792
When in Egypt,
drink straight from the source...


456
00:45:34.376 --> 00:45:37.959
What's wrong? Do you think I'm funny?

457
00:45:38.126 --> 00:45:40.834
I think you're amusing.

458
00:45:41.626 --> 00:45:43.459
So can I kiss you?

459
00:45:43.626 --> 00:45:49.209
I have a very interesting collection
of video tapes in the other room...


460
00:46:27.376 --> 00:46:28.792
Did I do something wrong?

461
00:46:29.334 --> 00:46:32.584
I don't know what happened.

462
00:46:32.876 --> 00:46:36.376
Got an awful headache...

463
00:46:37.751 --> 00:46:40.001
Mr Dmochowski,
I can't have you ordering a painting


464
00:46:40.167 --> 00:46:42.334
and then not paying
because you're short on money.


465
00:46:42.501 --> 00:46:45.751
I set that one aside
and you end up buying another one.


466
00:46:46.292 --> 00:46:49.292
I'm not in a rush to sell my paintings,
but I consider them sold!


467
00:46:49.459 --> 00:46:51.501
You're asking too much, I'm scared.

468
00:46:52.376 --> 00:46:55.459
And don't tell me
what you'd like me to paint!


469
00:46:55.626 --> 00:46:58.876
Let's not talk about my art,
or anyone else's.


470
00:46:59.042 --> 00:47:00.751
It just blocks my creativity.

471
00:47:01.126 --> 00:47:02.584
Yes, yes.

472
00:47:03.167 --> 00:47:06.917
I made you a list of records to buy.
Remember to get the right ones.


473
00:47:07.084 --> 00:47:09.751
I'll trade them for a few paintings.

474
00:47:11.334 --> 00:47:13.126
I know, yes.

475
00:47:13.501 --> 00:47:18.001
I understand. Thank you.
Best regards to your wife.


476
00:47:46.959 --> 00:47:48.917
All right...

477
00:47:50.667 --> 00:47:54.001
I'm going to pinch your butt.

478
00:47:54.167 --> 00:47:56.792
Be a brave boy.

479
00:48:05.834 --> 00:48:07.667
Press down on it.

480
00:48:08.667 --> 00:48:10.834
You'll live.

481
00:49:33.334 --> 00:49:34.626
E-fucking-nough!

482
00:49:41.709 --> 00:49:43.542
Enough of the fucking babysitting!

483
00:49:55.542 --> 00:49:58.876
- Tomek, what are you doing?
- Are you blind or what?


484
00:49:59.126 --> 00:50:01.751
I'm smashing up the fucking kitchen!

485
00:51:06.709 --> 00:51:08.251
<i>Beksinski, get out.</i>

486
00:51:08.417 --> 00:51:11.209
<i>There, there, Zosia... 
It's nothing.</i>

487
00:51:34.334 --> 00:51:36.292
<i>Have mercy...</i>

488
00:51:44.417 --> 00:51:49.292
Maybe you're too rough about...

489
00:51:49.709 --> 00:51:50.834
These things.

490
00:51:51.001 --> 00:51:54.084
I'm not rough about these things.

491
00:51:54.751 --> 00:51:58.209
I only feel something when I want
to undress someone. Later - nothing.


492
00:51:58.376 --> 00:52:02.126
Because you ought to slowly
get used to that someone.


493
00:52:02.292 --> 00:52:05.084
Slowly, gradually, bit by bit...

494
00:52:05.251 --> 00:52:10.084
Don't you get it?
I don't feel anything at all.


495
00:52:10.501 --> 00:52:13.709
Even if I feel anything,
it's more like revulsion.


496
00:52:13.876 --> 00:52:16.792
When I think about men -
Jeez, they disgust me,


497
00:52:16.959 --> 00:52:20.876
couldn't even touch them! And women...

498
00:52:23.626 --> 00:52:27.084
I don't really want them.

499
00:52:30.042 --> 00:52:34.084
It's ridiculous
and I can't take it anymore.


500
00:52:34.959 --> 00:52:36.917
Their constant chatter
gets on my nerves.


501
00:52:37.084 --> 00:52:40.334
All that humor,
all these jokes, those stories


502
00:52:40.501 --> 00:52:44.459
about your friend's dog
puking or something...


503
00:52:44.626 --> 00:52:47.792
Why should I give a fuck?

504
00:52:50.667 --> 00:52:54.792
When did you lock yourself into this box?

505
00:52:54.959 --> 00:52:58.459
- You used to be different.
- What box?


506
00:52:58.626 --> 00:53:03.959
That's how I see your
total disregard for other people.


507
00:53:04.126 --> 00:53:08.709
- When Betti started smoking.
- Oh, Tomek...


508
00:53:10.876 --> 00:53:15.792
- Guess I should kill myself after all.
- Don't talk like this!


509
00:53:15.959 --> 00:53:20.376
Back then I already knew
I should get it over with for good,


510
00:53:20.542 --> 00:53:25.126
but everyone
kept telling me I shouldn't...


511
00:53:25.334 --> 00:53:29.001
- Tell me, I want to understand.
- Even back then I couldn't take it.


512
00:53:29.167 --> 00:53:36.459
How could the fact of someone picking up
smoking be so devastating, though?


513
00:53:36.626 --> 00:53:40.042
How many times did I tell you
not to take it literally?


514
00:53:40.209 --> 00:53:42.709
How many times?!

515
00:53:42.876 --> 00:53:45.876
All right,
baby, tell me what's going on.


516
00:53:46.042 --> 00:53:49.709
What's going on is,
I had this perfect concept


517
00:53:49.876 --> 00:53:53.917
of the way everything was:
my life, the world, other people...


518
00:53:54.084 --> 00:53:58.126
And the person I was in love with -
but not like a normal guy,


519
00:53:58.292 --> 00:54:00.209
because I'm not normal
in the first place.


520
00:54:00.376 --> 00:54:05.167
But how did you get the idea
that perfection was real?


521
00:54:06.084 --> 00:54:08.459
Do you think you're perfect?

522
00:54:08.626 --> 00:54:10.667
How did I get this idea?

523
00:54:10.959 --> 00:54:15.667
- From books, movies, and songs!
- What do you mean?


524
00:54:15.834 --> 00:54:18.834
Even song lyrics talk about problems...

525
00:54:19.001 --> 00:54:24.001
Sure, but Good always wins.
Everyone's happy and huggy,


526
00:54:25.209 --> 00:54:29.459
love is pure, beautiful,
and immaculate, and so on...


527
00:54:29.626 --> 00:54:33.792
How do you think
people end up with love like this?


528
00:54:33.959 --> 00:54:38.876
It's a long,
long road to this kind of love.


529
00:54:39.042 --> 00:54:43.542
- Sure, sure... But it's out there.
- It is.


530
00:54:44.876 --> 00:54:48.667
- And it doesn't exist in the real world!
- You're wrong. It exists.


531
00:54:48.834 --> 00:54:50.084
The fuck it does!

532
00:54:50.251 --> 00:54:53.376
You convinced yourself
that it's not real...


533
00:54:53.542 --> 00:54:57.959
But it exists. 
I believe it does.

534
00:55:04.959 --> 00:55:08.876
It's claustrophobic.
I can't get out of this.


535
00:55:10.792 --> 00:55:14.542
Wherever I go,
I have to act like other people,


536
00:55:14.709 --> 00:55:18.084
do what everyone else does.

537
00:55:18.251 --> 00:55:24.459
I've got to play a role to get
the things I want or to be liked.


538
00:55:24.709 --> 00:55:29.251
I have to keep acting.
I can't get out of this.


539
00:55:29.417 --> 00:55:31.167
- You don't have to.
- I'm fed up.


540
00:55:31.334 --> 00:55:33.959
You're not yourself.

541
00:55:34.126 --> 00:55:37.834
You're right... 
I'm not myself.

542
00:55:41.042 --> 00:55:42.667
Why?

543
00:55:43.584 --> 00:55:48.042
You ought to get back to yourself,
step by step.


544
00:55:48.209 --> 00:55:52.751
But there's no myself anymore!
I don't exist anymore!


545
00:55:52.917 --> 00:55:56.792
I'm my own corpse or something.

546
00:56:00.042 --> 00:56:05.417
I could run a concentration camp
and get some payback...


547
00:56:06.084 --> 00:56:10.584
- For what?
- For being alive. For living.


548
00:56:18.126 --> 00:56:21.334
Life is the greatest gift of all!

549
00:56:23.126 --> 00:56:28.001
Fat lot of good it gave me.
Such a wonderful gift!


550
00:56:28.167 --> 00:56:32.542
What'd it get me? Fuck...
Tell me, what do I get out of it?


551
00:56:32.709 --> 00:56:35.834
What did it get me?

552
00:56:36.167 --> 00:56:40.167
No, you tell me
what you did to feel this gift.


553
00:56:41.334 --> 00:56:45.292
- The gift of life.
- Why should I work for it, though?


554
00:56:46.334 --> 00:56:48.167
Have I wanted it?

555
00:56:48.334 --> 00:56:50.709
I'm asking you, did I want it?

556
00:56:51.709 --> 00:56:53.792
The fuck should I work for it?

557
00:56:53.959 --> 00:56:56.542
- Tell me, Tomek...
- I'm fed up.


558
00:57:01.251 --> 00:57:05.376
Do you like it?
Does being this way make you happy?


559
00:57:07.167 --> 00:57:08.709
Don't you want to change?

560
00:57:08.876 --> 00:57:13.001
Oh sure, it makes me
masochistically happy!


561
00:57:13.167 --> 00:57:16.334
I can't and don't want
to get out of this.


562
00:57:16.501 --> 00:57:20.292
- You've never tried to change.
- Dad sees it too.


563
00:57:28.209 --> 00:57:31.334
3 days ago we went to the movies.

564
00:57:31.501 --> 00:57:36.626
I watched you a
few days before that, too,

565
00:57:36.834 --> 00:57:39.376
and you seemed absolutely fine.

566
00:57:39.542 --> 00:57:42.209
What happened
over the last couple of days?


567
00:57:44.542 --> 00:57:46.584
Nothing happened.

568
00:57:48.751 --> 00:57:52.001
Except for the fact
that if you keep carrying a heavy load,


569
00:57:52.167 --> 00:57:56.501
eventually you'll get tired.
I just fell over yesterday.


570
00:57:56.667 --> 00:58:02.751
- I didn't see you carrying a load.
- I'm glad you didn't!


571
00:58:03.084 --> 00:58:06.626
Your dad and I want to help you.

572
00:58:06.959 --> 00:58:10.667
We're showing you kindness and heart,

573
00:58:10.834 --> 00:58:14.667
we're reaching out to you,
but you want to cut off our hands...


574
00:58:14.834 --> 00:58:19.334
- Why?
- You literally cannot do anything!


575
00:58:19.501 --> 00:58:22.126
What's the point
of all that goddamn talking?


576
00:58:50.251 --> 00:58:51.626
Zosia...

577
00:58:51.709 --> 00:58:53.584
I have a sore right there...

578
00:58:56.709 --> 00:59:00.251
- It hurts...
- Maybe cupping would help her.


579
00:59:00.417 --> 00:59:04.542
Cupping over damaged skin?!
Go back to bed, Ma!


580
00:59:07.292 --> 00:59:08.876
It hurts!

581
00:59:10.501 --> 00:59:12.501
Good grief...

582
00:59:14.751 --> 00:59:18.417
- How about this one?
- Yes, it's happier.


583
00:59:23.251 --> 00:59:27.251
- It hurts, Zosia...
- I know, Mother.


584
00:59:30.751 --> 00:59:33.542
- Thank you.
- Get some rest.


585
01:00:00.334 --> 01:00:03.209
Come back to me, son!

586
01:00:03.417 --> 01:00:05.001
Do you hear me? Come back!

587
01:00:06.459 --> 01:00:08.209
Don't you leave your mom!

588
01:00:08.542 --> 01:00:11.167
Come back, baby...

589
01:00:12.042 --> 01:00:13.667
There's only room for one.

590
01:00:17.792 --> 01:00:20.501
You go, I'll catch up.

591
01:00:56.459 --> 01:00:58.251
Maybe it's wrong to save him.

592
01:00:58.417 --> 01:01:00.959
Listen, you have a lot of clout
in this place...


593
01:01:01.126 --> 01:01:03.042
Stop it!

594
01:01:05.167 --> 01:01:08.209
He didn't want to live.
He's just going to suffer.


595
01:01:08.626 --> 01:01:12.251
- Come on, I'll give you a shot.
- No, I'm fine.


596
01:01:12.542 --> 01:01:15.001
He was just afraid to live!

597
01:01:15.626 --> 01:01:18.251
I think suicide
is a very brave and courageous act.


598
01:01:18.417 --> 01:01:20.501
If he decided to end it, we should...

599
01:01:20.667 --> 01:01:24.876
Sorry, that's nonsense.
Why did you call the ambulance, then?


600
01:01:25.376 --> 01:01:27.334
What about the cops?

601
01:01:32.042 --> 01:01:34.459
- Fill her up, please.
- OK.


602
01:02:06.334 --> 01:02:07.501
Too bad...

603
01:02:15.084 --> 01:02:17.626
I wouldn't want to go like that.

604
01:02:21.292 --> 01:02:26.917
I'd like to die before you.
I think women have it worse.


605
01:02:27.834 --> 01:02:30.417
Men just sort of...

606
01:02:37.126 --> 01:02:39.376
Is Madame still alive?

607
01:02:41.709 --> 01:02:44.459
The way a plant is alive...

608
01:02:48.542 --> 01:02:50.334
Excuse me, Zosia.

609
01:03:29.167 --> 01:03:33.167
<i>Have you watched Herzog's
"Nosferatu" with Klaus Kinski?</i>


610
01:03:33.501 --> 01:03:36.459
<i>Yes. Wonderful film.</i>

611
01:03:38.834 --> 01:03:42.251
<i>Phenomenal. 
Simply phenomenal!</i>

612
01:03:42.417 --> 01:03:44.626
<i>I saw it around 5 times...</i>

613
01:03:46.126 --> 01:03:48.459
<i>Want some Coke?</i>

614
01:03:51.417 --> 01:03:58.042
<i>- Got to show the whole thing...
- Do an awful closeup!</i>


615
01:04:00.209 --> 01:04:02.251
<i>You can start zooming now.</i>

616
01:04:03.042 --> 01:04:08.584
<i>You're standing so far apart
I can't get you both in the frame...</i>


617
01:04:12.084 --> 01:04:14.376
Hello, everyone!

618
01:04:14.792 --> 01:04:17.667
We hope you're ready for an exciting ride!

619
01:04:17.834 --> 01:04:22.084
You'll get to see another chapter
of the adventures of 007.


620
01:04:22.251 --> 01:04:24.417
Plenty of shooting, plenty of intrigue

621
01:04:24.584 --> 01:04:27.209
and a cherry on top:

622
01:04:27.209 --> 01:04:32.751
the gorgeous Barbara Bach
as Major Amasova!


623
01:04:33.709 --> 01:04:36.209
Think everyone already here, right?

624
01:04:36.376 --> 01:04:42.709
Okay, folks, get ready
for Tomasz Beksinski and Roger Moore!


625
01:05:25.626 --> 01:05:27.792
Roger Moore...

626
01:05:28.251 --> 01:05:32.334
As James Bond, 007,

627
01:05:33.959 --> 01:05:38.542
in "The Spy Who Loved Me".

628
01:05:47.459 --> 01:05:49.251
Also starring...

629
01:05:53.834 --> 01:05:56.334
...the grave of Johannes
Hevelius was discovered


630
01:05:56.417 --> 01:05:58.042
at St Catherine's Church in GdaĆsk,

631
01:05:58.084 --> 01:06:00.876
exactly one year before the 300th
anniversary of his...


632
01:06:04.792 --> 01:06:06.626
How are you, Tomek? What's up?

633
01:06:06.792 --> 01:06:09.251
Nothing.

634
01:06:12.501 --> 01:06:13.751
Hi, Tomek!

635
01:06:16.376 --> 01:06:19.209
- Good morning.
- I brought you some new records.


636
01:06:31.334 --> 01:06:32.834
- Are we recording?
- Yes.


637
01:06:35.876 --> 01:06:37.459
This is tape no. 2...

638
01:06:38.417 --> 01:06:40.292
Say what day it is, will you?

639
01:06:40.834 --> 01:06:45.917
Today is July 19, 1986.

640
01:06:47.584 --> 01:06:52.126
We're picking up
after a brief bathroom break.


641
01:06:55.042 --> 01:06:59.417
Zdzislaw Beksinski and Piotr Dmochowski.

642
01:06:59.459 --> 01:07:02.917
No, there aren't any
splatters, Grzesiek.


643
01:07:02.917 --> 01:07:06.251
I recorded it <i>as</i> well
and watched it.


644
01:07:06.292 --> 01:07:09.542
My copy is exactly the same.

645
01:07:09.959 --> 01:07:13.376
Okay, bring it over to my folks
as usual and we'll see.


646
01:07:15.917 --> 01:07:18.084
Jesus, I'm stuffed!

647
01:07:18.251 --> 01:07:22.126
That makes me glad. 
I'm happy for you.

648
01:07:23.126 --> 01:07:25.209
It was great.

649
01:07:25.792 --> 01:07:28.792
Could you go sit
with Granny Beksinska for a bit?


650
01:07:28.959 --> 01:07:32.876
No, her room stinks
bad enough to make me puke.


651
01:07:34.959 --> 01:07:37.626
She's the only mom your dad has.

652
01:07:37.792 --> 01:07:40.126
She was your favorite grandma
when you were little.


653
01:07:40.292 --> 01:07:42.917
She went with you
to put up your death notices.


654
01:07:43.084 --> 01:07:48.292
Fine, all right, is that supposed
to make her stink any less?


655
01:07:49.209 --> 01:07:51.417
Where is that thing...

656
01:07:51.584 --> 01:07:52.834
It was right here.

657
01:07:54.126 --> 01:07:56.542
- Where's the bottle opener?
- I moved it.


658
01:08:05.084 --> 01:08:07.917
You keep saying a
lot of bad things, son.

659
01:08:09.126 --> 01:08:11.626
You keep hurting everyone

660
01:08:11.792 --> 01:08:17.417
and never, not even once,
think how difficult it is for us.


661
01:08:23.126 --> 01:08:24.876
Do you hear me?

662
01:09:10.417 --> 01:09:11.625
<i>Good morning!</i>

663
01:09:12.209 --> 01:09:15.334
<i>I can smell it was a busy night.</i>

664
01:09:15.501 --> 01:09:17.417
<i>How are you today, baby girl?</i>

665
01:09:18.542 --> 01:09:23.834
<i>Eyes wide open? That's progress!
All right, give us some steam.</i>


666
01:09:51.376 --> 01:09:54.417
You gave us a good run, Mother.

667
01:09:56.084 --> 01:09:59.792
89 years is a great result,
but Grandma Stankiewicz


668
01:09:59.959 --> 01:10:05.209
is moving toward a beautiful finish
at 90 years so far...


669
01:10:12.292 --> 01:10:15.042
Zosia! Beksinska is dead!

670
01:10:56.542 --> 01:10:57.584
Can I have two?

671
01:10:57.751 --> 01:11:00.084
- Of course!
- Thanks.


672
01:11:00.251 --> 01:11:05.292
Excuse me,
how long until we land in Rzeszow?


673
01:11:05.584 --> 01:11:06.584
10 minutes.

674
01:11:06.751 --> 01:11:11.459
That's funny.
I saw my numerologist yesterday


675
01:11:11.709 --> 01:11:14.667
and he calculated
that this plane was going to crash.


676
01:11:14.834 --> 01:11:18.042
Fancy that! Weren't you scared
to take this flight, then?


677
01:11:18.209 --> 01:11:21.542
No, he also calculated that I'd make it.

678
01:11:21.709 --> 01:11:24.292
Do you like wasting
your money on nonsense?


679
01:11:25.626 --> 01:11:27.376
I like nonsense.

680
01:11:47.209 --> 01:11:49.792
- Here you go.
- God bless you, young man.


681
01:11:50.626 --> 01:11:53.584
May the good Lord
grant you a lot of children.


682
01:12:01.917 --> 01:12:03.251
Here we go...

683
01:12:38.417 --> 01:12:40.042
Jesus!

684
01:13:14.542 --> 01:13:16.209
Faster, faster!

685
01:13:20.292 --> 01:13:21.792
Out, out.

686
01:13:26.751 --> 01:13:29.001
Jesus, there's a woman stuck in here!

687
01:13:29.167 --> 01:13:31.709
Help me get her out!

688
01:13:33.084 --> 01:13:36.251
Come on, help me!

689
01:13:44.376 --> 01:13:45.626
Faster!

690
01:14:20.542 --> 01:14:24.834
At midnight, in the month of July,
A mystic moon hangs in the sky.


691
01:14:26.167 --> 01:14:27.626
Good evening.

692
01:14:27.792 --> 01:14:32.917
This nighttime meeting
will be quite special.


693
01:14:34.042 --> 01:14:37.084
I'm going to try
to tell you a story - amazing,


694
01:14:37.251 --> 01:14:40.709
incredible, straddling
the boundary of dreams and reality.


695
01:14:42.001 --> 01:14:46.709
Partly made up and partly true...

696
01:14:47.751 --> 01:14:52.251
And thus, the tale which will take up

697
01:14:52.417 --> 01:14:56.334
took place a long time ago...

698
01:15:21.417 --> 01:15:26.084
What are you bad at, in your opinion?

699
01:15:27.417 --> 01:15:29.126
At everything.

700
01:15:33.751 --> 01:15:37.501
I even feel inferior to many painters.

701
01:15:38.751 --> 01:15:44.626
I immediately feel all the things
I don't do well enough,


702
01:15:45.126 --> 01:15:48.292
I feel everything I can't do.

703
01:15:50.001 --> 01:15:52.917
Right now I can't see
the things I'm better at.


704
01:15:53.417 --> 01:15:58.417
So for you
it's not a matter of internal strife.


705
01:15:59.126 --> 01:16:02.334
You want to be better than everyone
else, and that's your problem,


706
01:16:02.501 --> 01:16:05.376
not some childhood issues
or external influence.


707
01:16:05.542 --> 01:16:10.126
I went through some strife,
don't you know.


708
01:16:10.959 --> 01:16:14.417
But it didn't make me...

709
01:16:15.792 --> 01:16:19.459
I have this sort of homeo...

710
01:16:20.334 --> 01:16:22.126
- What do you call it?
- Homeostatic...?


711
01:16:22.292 --> 01:16:26.917
Precisely. A homeostatic system
that makes me quickly regain balance.


712
01:16:27.084 --> 01:16:32.292
My son doesn't have one.
He has an anti-homeostatic system.


713
01:16:32.667 --> 01:16:35.584
Every tiny thing triggers an avalanche.

714
01:16:37.167 --> 01:16:39.542
If you're in a boat

715
01:16:39.709 --> 01:16:43.626
heading for a waterfall
which means certain death,


716
01:16:43.792 --> 01:16:47.792
and there's a cactus
and an easy chair with you in that boat,


717
01:16:47.959 --> 01:16:54.001
it'd be better to sit in that chair
instead of on the cactus, right?


718
01:16:54.501 --> 01:16:57.251
Hope the new year brings you
